definition.value: A secondary amino compound that is 3,4-dimethoxyphenylethylamine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen has been replaced by a 4-cyano-4-(3,4-dimethoxyphenyl)-5-methylhexyl group.
2-(3,4-dimethoxyphenyl)-5-{[2-(3,4-dimethoxyphenyl)ethyl]amino}-2-(propan-2-yl)pentanenitrile that has S configuration.
2-(3,4-dimethoxyphenyl)-5-{[2-(3,4-dimethoxyphenyl)ethyl]amino}-2-(propan-2-yl)pentanenitrile that has R configuration.
An activator that activates the  hypoxia inducible factor (HIF) pathway.
Any anthocyanin cation carrying a 3-hydroxy substituent.
Any hydroxyflavan containing a 3-hydroxy group and having 2R,3R stereochemistry.
An oxonium betaine obtained by deprotonation of the 3-hydroxy group of any 3-hydroxyanthocyanidin cation. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
Any hydroxyflavan containing a 3-hydroxy group and having 2S,3R stereochemistry.
Any hydroxyflavan containing a 3-hydroxy group and having 2S,3S stereochemistry.
Any glycoside derived from N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine.

An organofluorine compound containing only C-F bonds (no C-H bonds) and C-C bonds but also other heteroatoms (particularly other halogens, oxygen, and sulfur). Their properties represent a blend of fluorocarbons (containing only C-F and C-C bonds) and the parent functionalised organic species.
An arsonium ion that is choline in which the central nitrogen has been replaced by arsenic.

An organophosphonate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of (acetamidomethyl)phosphonic acid, obtained by deprotonation of one of the phosphonate OH groups. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
An aromatic ether that is diphenyl ether carrying between 2 and 10 bromo substituents attached to the two benzene rings.
A nucleobase analogue obtained by addition of an etheno group across positions N2 and 3 of guanine.
A nucleobase analogue obtained by addition of an etheno group across positions 1 and N2 of guanine.

A polysaccharide derivative consisting of a repeating unit of beta-D-glucuronosyl, beta-D-galacturonosyl and N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl residues linked sequentially (1->3) and (1->3), to the glucuronosyl and N-acetylglucosaminyl residues of which are linked respectively (1->2) and (1->6) an N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl residue and an alpha-D-glucosyl residue, while the galacturonosyl residue forms an amide with L-threonine, the complete pentasaccharide repeating units all being linked (1->4). The O-polysaccharide of Proteus mirabilis O11.

An organophosphonate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of (S)-(1-aminoethyl)phosphonic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the phosphonate OH groups and protonation of the amino group. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.

An organophosphonate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of [(1S)-1-acetamidoethyl]phosphonic acid, obtained by deprotonation of one of the phosphonate OH groups. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A methylthymine in which the methyl group is located at the O4-position.
A pyrimidone that is thymine bearing a single methyl substituent.
A 2-amino-4-oxopentanoic acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of (R)-2-amino-4-oxopentanoic acid; major microspecies at pH 7.3.
An N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion that is the conjugate base of N-arachidonoyl-L-leucine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An oxopurine that is adenine bearing a single oxo substituent at position 8.
A nucleobase analogue that is adenine bearing a single hydroxy substituent at position 8.
A methyladenine in which the methyl substituent is located at position 4.
An L-threonine derivative obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-({4-[(morpholin-4-yl)methyl]phenyl}ethynyl)benzoic acid with the amino group of N-hydroxy-L-threoninamide.
Any compound that inhibits the biosynthesis of any lipopolysaccharide.
An EC 3.5.1.* (non-peptide linear amide C-N hydrolase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of UDP-3-O-acyl-N-acetylglucosamine deacetylase (EC 3.5.1.108).
A hydroperoxyoctadecatrienoate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group of (9Z,11S,12Z,15Z)-11-hydroperoxyoctadecatrienoic acid. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A triglyceride in which the three acyl groups contain a total of 60 carbons and 13 double bonds.
A triglyceride in which the three acyl groups contain a total of 60 carbons and 12 double bonds.
A triglyceride in which the three acyl groups contain a total of 60 carbons and 11 double bonds.
A triglyceride in which the three acyl groups contain a total of 62 carbons and 14 double bonds.
A triglyceride in which the three acyl groups contain a total of 62 carbons and 13 double bonds.
A bile acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of alpha-muricholic acid. The major species at pH 7.3.
A triterpenyl phosphate that is presqualene in which the hydroxy hydrogen has been replaced by a monophosphate group.

A polysaccharide derivative consisting of a repeating unit of beta-D-glucuronosyl, beta-D-galacturonosyl and N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl residues linked sequentially (1->3) and (1->3), to the glucuronosyl residue of which is linked (1->2) an N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl residue, while the galacturonosyl residue forms an amide with L-threonine, the complete tetrasaccharide repeating units all being linked (1->4). The O-polysaccharide of Proteus mirabilis 9B-m.
A bile acid anion resulting from deprotonation of the carboxy group of beta-muricholic acid (i.e. the conjugate base of beta-muricholic acid). It is the major species at pH 7.3.

A polysaccharide derivative consisting of a repeating unit of beta-D-glucuronosyl, beta-D-galacturonosyl and N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl residues linked sequentially (1->3) and (1->3), to the glucuronosyl and N-acetylglucosaminyl residues of which are linked respectively (1->2) and (1->6) an N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl residue and an alpha-D-glucosyl residue, while the galacturonosyl residue forms an amide with 3-O-acetyl-L-threonine, the complete pentasaccharide repeating units all being linked (1->4). The O-polysaccharide of Proteus  genomospecies 3J-r.
An N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of N-oleoyl-L-isoleucine. The major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy groups of N-oleoyl-L-glutamic acid. The major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acyl-amino acid in which amino acid component is specified as serine.
A cholanic acid anion, that is the conjugate base of 1beta-hydroxydeoxycholic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.

A tetrahydronicotinamide adenine dinucleotide obtained by formal stereo- and regioselective hydration across the 5,6-double bond in the nicotinyl ring of NADH, with the hydroxy group located at position 6, having (R)-configuration.
A mixture consisting of equimolar amounts of picrotoxinin and picrotin found in the climbing plant Anamirta cocculus.
A 1-monoglyceride in which the acyl group contains 16 carbons and is fully saturated.
A 1-monoglyceride in which the acyl group contains 16 carbons and 1 double bond.
A 1-monoglyceride in which the acyl group contains 18 carbons and is fully saturated.
